wikipedia.org/wiki/Complex_number" title=3D"Complex number">complex</a> num=
ber).
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_vector" title=3D"=
Euclidean vector">Geometrically, vectors</a> are multi-<a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dimension" title=3D"Dimension">dimensional</a> quantit=
ies with magnitude and direction, often pictured as arrows. A linear transf=
ormation <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rotation_(mathematics)" t=
itle=3D"Rotation (mathematics)">rotates</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Scaling_(geometry)" title=3D"Scaling (geometry)">stretches</a>, =
or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shear_mapping" title=3D"Shear m=
apping">shears</a> the vectors upon which it acts. A linear transformation'=
s eigenvectors are those vectors that are only stretched or shrunk, with ne=
ither rotation nor shear. The corresponding eigenvalue is the factor by whi=
ch an eigenvector is stretched or shrunk. If the eigenvalue is negative, th=
e eigenvector's direction is reversed.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEBurdenFai=
res1993401_1-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Eigenvalues_and_eigenvectors#cite_note-FOOTNOTEBurdenFaires1993401-1"><sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup>
</p><p>The eigenvectors and eigenvalues of a linear transformation serve to=
 characterize it, and so they play important roles in all areas where linea=
r algebra is applied, from <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geology=
" title=3D"Geology">geology</a> to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Quantum_mechanics" title=3D"Quantum mechanics">quantum mechanics</a>. In p=
articular, it is often the case that a system is represented by a linear tr=
ansformation whose outputs are fed as inputs to the same transformation (<a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Feedback" title=3D"Feedback">feedbac=
k</a>).  In such an application, the largest eigenvalue is of particular im=
portance, because it governs the long-term behavior of the system after man=
y applications of the linear transformation, and the associated eigenvector=
 is the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Steady_state" title=3D"Ste=
ady state">steady state</a> of the system.
</p>
