"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eigenvalues_and_eigenv=
ectors#cite_note-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Given an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dimension_(vector_=
space)" title=3D"Dimension (vector space)"><i>n</i>-dimensional vector spac=
e</a> and a choice of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Basis_(linea=
r_algebra)" title=3D"Basis (linear algebra)">basis</a>, there is a direct c=
orrespondence between linear transformations from the vector space into its=
elf and <i>n</i>-by-<i>n</i> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Squar=
e_matrix" title=3D"Square matrix">square matrices</a>. Hence, in a finite-d=
imensional vector space, it is equivalent to define eigenvalues and eigenve=
ctors using either the language of linear transformations, or the language =
of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Matrix_(mathematics)" title=3D"=
Matrix (mathematics)">matrices</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEHerstein1964=
228,_229_3-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Eigenvalues_and_eigenvectors#cite_note-FOOTNOTEHerstein1964228,_229-3"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a>=
</sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTENering197038_4-0" class=3D"reference"><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eigenvalues_and_eigenvectors#cite_not=
e-FOOTNOTENering197038-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Overview">Overview</h2><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DEigenvalues_and_eige=
nvectors&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D2" title=3D"Edit section: Overview=
"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></spa=
n></div>
<p>Eigenvalues and eigenvectors feature prominently in the analysis of line=
ar transformations. The prefix <i><a href=3D"https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki=
/eigen-" class=3D"extiw" title=3D"wikt:eigen-">eigen-</a></i> is adopted fr=
om the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/German_language" title=3D"G=
erman language">German</a> <a href=3D"https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/eigen#=
German" class=3D"extiw" title=3D"wikt:eigen"><span title=3D"German-language=
 text"><i lang=3D"de">eigen</i></span></a> (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Cognate" title=3D"Cognate">cognate</a> with the <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/English_language" title=3D"English language">Englis=
h</a> word <i><a href=3D"https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/own#English" class=
=3D"extiw" title=3D"wikt:own">own</a></i>) for 'proper', 'characteristic', =
'own'.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEBetteridge1965_5-0" class=3D"reference"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eigenvalues_and_eigenvectors#cite_n=
ote-FOOTNOTEBetteridge1965-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-:0_6-0" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eigenvalues_and_eig=
envectors#cite_note-:0-6"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>6<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Originally used to study <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Principal_axis_(mechanics)" class=3D"mw-redirec=
t" title=3D"Principal axis (mechanics)">principal axes</a> of the rotationa=
l motion of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rigid_body" title=3D"R=
igid body">rigid bodies</a>, eigenvalues and eigenvectors have a wide range=
 of applications, for example in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/S=
tability_theory" title=3D"Stability theory">stability analysis</a>, <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vibration_analysis#eigenvalue_problem" cl=
ass=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Vibration analysis">vibration analysis</a>, <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Atomic_orbital" title=3D"Atomic orbi=
tal">atomic orbitals</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eigenfac=
e" title=3D"Eigenface">facial recognition</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Eigendecomposition_of_a_matrix" title=3D"Eigendecompositio=
n of a matrix">matrix diagonalization</a>.
</p><p>In essence, an eigenvector <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>v</b></span> o=
f a linear transformation <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:=
italic;">T</span> is a nonzero vector that, when <span class=3D"texhtml mva=
r" style=3D"font-style:italic;">T</span> is applied to it, does not change =
direction. Applying <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic=
;">T</span> to the eigenvector only scales the eigenvector by the scalar va=
lue <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">=CE=BB</span>=
, called an eigenvalue. This condition can be written as the equation
<span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-block"><span class=3D"mwe-=
math-mathml-display mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math di=
splay=3D"block" xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\d=
isplaystyle T(\mathbf {v} )=3D\lambda \mathbf {v} ,}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mi>T</mi>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">(</mo>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mi mathvariant=3D"bold">v</mi>
        </mrow>
        <mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mi>=CE=BB<!-- =CE=BB --></mi>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mi mathvariant=3D"bold">v</mi>
        </mrow>
        <mo>,</mo>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle T(\mathbf {v}=
 )=3D\lambda \mathbf {v} ,}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
