(\mathbf {v} )=3D\lambda \mathbf {v} ,}"></span>
referred to as the <b>eigenvalue equation</b> or <b>eigenequation</b>. In g=
eneral, <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">=CE=BB</s=
pan> may be any <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scalar_(mathematic=
s)" title=3D"Scalar (mathematics)">scalar</a>. For example, <span class=3D"=
texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">=CE=BB</span> may be negative, i=
n which case the eigenvector reverses direction as part of the scaling, or =
it may be zero or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Complex_number" =
title=3D"Complex number">complex</a>.
</p>
<figure typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/F=
ile:Mona_Lisa_eigenvector_grid.png" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=
