"><span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">n</span>=E2=80=
=89=C3=97=E2=80=891</span></span> matrix. For a matrix, eigenvalues and eig=
envectors can be used to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Matrix_de=
composition" title=3D"Matrix decomposition">decompose the matrix</a>=E2=80=
=94for example by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diagonalizable_m=
atrix" title=3D"Diagonalizable matrix">diagonalizing</a> it.
</p><p>Eigenvalues and eigenvectors give rise to many closely related mathe=
matical concepts, and the prefix <i>eigen-</i> is applied liberally when na=
ming them:
</p>
<ul><li>The set of all eigenvectors of a linear transformation, each paired=
 with its corresponding eigenvalue, is called the <b>eigensystem</b> of tha=
t transformation.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEPressTeukolskyVetterlingFlanne=
ry2007536_7-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Eigenvalues_and_eigenvectors#cite_note-FOOTNOTEPressTeukolskyVetterlingFla=
nnery2007536-7"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEWolfram.com:_Eigenvec=
tor_8-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eigen=
values_and_eigenvectors#cite_note-FOOTNOTEWolfram.com:_Eigenvector-8"><span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>8<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a><=
/sup></li>
<li>The set of all eigenvectors of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"fo=
nt-style:italic;">T</span> corresponding to the same eigenvalue, together w=
ith the zero vector, is called an <b>eigenspace</b>, or the <b>characterist=
ic space</b> of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">T=
</span> associated with that eigenvalue.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTENering1=
970107_9-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ei=
genvalues_and_eigenvectors#cite_note-FOOTNOTENering1970107-9"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>9<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><=
/li>
<li>If a set of eigenvectors of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-=
style:italic;">T</span> forms a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ba=
sis_(linear_algebra)" title=3D"Basis (linear algebra)">basis</a> of the dom=
ain of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">T</span>, =
then this basis is called an <b>eigenbasis</b>.</li></ul>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"History">History</h2><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DEigenvalues_and_eigenv=
ectors&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D3" title=3D"Edit section: History"><=
span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span><=
/div>
<p>Eigenvalues are often introduced in the context of <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_algebra" title=3D"Linear algebra">linear algebra=
</a> or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Matrix_(mathematics)" titl=
e=3D"Matrix (mathematics)">matrix theory</a>. Historically, however, they a=
rose in the study of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quadratic_for=
m" title=3D"Quadratic form">quadratic forms</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Differential_equation" title=3D"Differential equation">di=
fferential equations</a>.
</p><p>In the 18th century, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Leonha=
rd_Euler" title=3D"Leonhard Euler">Leonhard Euler</a> studied the rotationa=
l motion of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rigid_body" title=3D=
"Rigid body">rigid body</a>, and discovered the importance of the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Moment_of_inertia#Principal_axes" title=
=3D"Moment of inertia">principal axes</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-10" class=3D"=
reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eigenvalues_and_eigenve=
ctors#cite_note-10"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>a<span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jos=
eph-Louis_Lagrange" title=3D"Joseph-Louis Lagrange">Joseph-Louis Lagrange</=
a> realized that the principal axes are the eigenvectors of the inertia mat=
rix.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEHawkins1975=C2=A72_11-0" class=3D"reference=
"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eigenvalues_and_eigenvectors#cit=
e_note-FOOTNOTEHawkins1975%C2%A72-11"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>=
10<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In the early 19th century, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Augustin-Louis_Cauchy" title=3D"Augustin-Louis Cauchy">Augustin-Louis Cauch=
y</a> saw how their work could be used to classify the <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quadric" title=3D"Quadric">quadric surfaces</a>, and g=
eneralized it to arbitrary dimensions.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEHawkins19=
75=C2=A73_12-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Eigenvalues_and_eigenvectors#cite_note-FOOTNOTEHawkins1975%C2%A73-12"><sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>11<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></=
a></sup> Cauchy also coined the term <i>racine caract=C3=A9ristique</i> (ch=
aracteristic root), for what is now called <i>eigenvalue</i>; his term surv=
ives in <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Characteristic_polynomi=
al" title=3D"Characteristic polynomial">characteristic equation</a></i>.<su=
p id=3D"cite_ref-13" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Eigenvalues_and_eigenvectors#cite_note-13"><span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">[</span>b<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Later, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joseph_Fourier" titl=
e=3D"Joseph Fourier">Joseph Fourier</a> used the work of Lagrange and <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pierre-Simon_Laplace" title=3D"Pierre-S=
imon Laplace">Pierre-Simon Laplace</a> to solve the <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Heat_equation" title=3D"Heat equation">heat equation</a> =
by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Separation_of_variables" title=
=3D"Separation of variables">separation of variables</a> in his 1822 treati=
se <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joseph_Fourier#The_Analytic_=
Theory_of_Heat" title=3D"Joseph Fourier">The Analytic Theory of Heat (Th=C3=
=A9orie analytique de la chaleur)</a></i>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKline=
1972p._673_14-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Eigenvalues_and_eigenvectors#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKline1972p._673-14"><span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>12<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a>=
</sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charles-Fran%C3%A7ois_Sturm=
" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Charles-Fran=C3=A7ois Sturm">Charles-Fran=
=C3=A7ois Sturm</a> elaborated on Fourier's ideas further, and brought them=
 to the attention of Cauchy, who combined them with his own ideas and arriv=
ed at the fact that real <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Symmetric=
_matrix" title=3D"Symmetric matrix">symmetric matrices</a> have real eigenv=
alues.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEHawkins1975=C2=A73_12-1" class=3D"referen=
ce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eigenvalues_and_eigenvectors#c=
ite_note-FOOTNOTEHawkins1975%C2%A73-12"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</spa=
n>11<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> This was extended by <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Charles_Hermite" title=3D"Charles He=
rmite">Charles Hermite</a> in 1855 to what are now called <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hermitian_matrix" title=3D"Hermitian matrix">Hermit=
ian matrices</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKline1972pp._807=E2=80=93808_1=
5-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eigenvalu=
es_and_eigenvectors#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKline1972pp._807%E2%80%93808-15"><spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>13<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup>
</p><p>Around the same time, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Franc=
esco_Brioschi" title=3D"Francesco Brioschi">Francesco Brioschi</a> proved t=
hat the eigenvalues of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orthogonal_=
matrix" title=3D"Orthogonal matrix">orthogonal matrices</a> lie on the <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unit_circle" title=3D"Unit circle">uni=
t circle</a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEHawkins1975=C2=A73_12-2" class=3D"=
reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eigenvalues_and_eigenve=
ctors#cite_note-FOOTNOTEHawkins1975%C2%A73-12"><span class=3D"cite-bracket"=
>[</span>11<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> and <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alfred_Clebsch" title=3D"Alfred Clebsch">Alfre=
d Clebsch</a> found the corresponding result for <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Skew-symmetric_matrix" title=3D"Skew-symmetric matrix">skew-=
symmetric matrices</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKline1972pp._807=E2=80=
=93808_15-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/E=
igenvalues_and_eigenvectors#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKline1972pp._807%E2%80%93808-=
15"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>13<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup> Finally, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Karl_Weie=
rstrass" title=3D"Karl Weierstrass">Karl Weierstrass</a> clarified an impor=
tant aspect in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stability_theor=
y" title=3D"Stability theory">stability theory</a> started by Laplace, by r=
ealizing that <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Defective_matrix" ti=
tle=3D"Defective matrix">defective matrices</a> can cause instability.<sup =
id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEHawkins1975=C2=A73_12-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eigenvalues_and_eigenvectors#cite_note-FO=
OTNOTEHawkins1975%C2%A73-12"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>11<span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In the meantime, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joseph_Lio=
uville" title=3D"Joseph Liouville">Joseph Liouville</a> studied eigenvalue =
problems similar to those of Sturm; the discipline that grew out of their w=
ork is now called <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sturm%E2%80%9=
3Liouville_theory" title=3D"Sturm=E2=80=93Liouville theory">Sturm=E2=80=93L=
iouville theory</a></i>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKline1972pp._715=E2=80=
=93716_16-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/E=
igenvalues_and_eigenvectors#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKline1972pp._715%E2%80%93716-=
16"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>14<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hermann_Schwarz" t=
itle=3D"Hermann Schwarz">Schwarz</a> studied the first eigenvalue of <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Laplace%27s_equation" title=3D"Laplace's=
 equation">Laplace's equation</a> on general domains towards the end of the=
 19th century, while <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Henri_Poincar=
%C3%A9" title=3D"Henri Poincar=C3=A9">Poincar=C3=A9</a> studied <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Poisson%27s_equation" title=3D"Poisson's equa=
tion">Poisson's equation</a> a few years later.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTE=
Kline1972pp._706=E2=80=93707_17-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eigenvalues_and_eigenvectors#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKline19=
72pp._706%E2%80%93707-17"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>15<span clas=
s=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>At the start of the 20th century, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/David_Hilbert" title=3D"David Hilbert">David Hilbert</a> studied the=
 eigenvalues of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integral_operator"=
 title=3D"Integral operator">integral operators</a> by viewing the operator=
s as infinite matrices.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKline19721063p._18-0" cl=
ass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eigenvalues_and_=
eigenvectors#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKline19721063p.-18"><span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">[</span>16<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> He was the f=
irst to use the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/German_language" t=
itle=3D"German language">German</a> word <i>eigen</i>, which means "own",<s=
up id=3D"cite_ref-:0_6-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Eigenvalues_and_eigenvectors#cite_note-:0-6"><span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">[</span>6<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> to deno=
te eigenvalues and eigenvectors in 1904,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-19" class=3D"re=
ference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eigenvalues_and_eigenvect=
ors#cite_note-19"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>c<span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">]</span></a></sup> though he may have been following a related us=
age by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hermann_von_Helmholtz" titl=
e=3D"Hermann von Helmholtz">Hermann von Helmholtz</a>. For some time, the s=
tandard term in English was "proper value", but the more distinctive term "=
eigenvalue" is the standard today.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEAldrich2006_2=
0-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eigenvalu=
es_and_eigenvectors#cite_note-FOOTNOTEAldrich2006-20"><span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">[</span>17<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The first numerical algorithm for computing eigenvalues and eigenvec=
tors appeared in 1929, when <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Richar=
d_von_Mises" title=3D"Richard von Mises">Richard von Mises</a> published th=
e <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Power_method" class=3D"mw-redire=
ct" title=3D"Power method">power method</a>. One of the most popular method=
s today, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/QR_algorithm" title=
=3D"QR algorithm">QR algorithm</a>, was proposed independently by <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_G._F._Francis" title=3D"John G. F. F=
rancis">John G. F. Francis</a><sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEFrancis1961265=E2=
=80=93271_21-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Eigenvalues_and_eigenvectors#cite_note-FOOTNOTEFrancis1961265%E2%80%93271=
-21"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>18<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]<=
/span></a></sup> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vera_Kublanov=
skaya" title=3D"Vera Kublanovskaya">Vera Kublanovskaya</a><sup id=3D"cite_r=
ef-FOOTNOTEKublanovskaya1962_22-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eigenvalues_and_eigenvectors#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKublano=
vskaya1962-22"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>19<span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">]</span></a></sup> in 1961.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEGolubVan_Loa=
n1996=C2=A77.3_23-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Eigenvalues_and_eigenvectors#cite_note-FOOTNOTEGolubVan_Loan1996%C2%=
A77.3-23"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>20<span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEMeyer2000=C2=A77.3_24-0" c=
lass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eigenvalues_and=
_eigenvectors#cite_note-FOOTNOTEMeyer2000%C2%A77.3-24"><span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">[</span>21<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Eigenvalues_and_eigenvector=
s_of_matrices">Eigenvalues and eigenvectors of matrices</h2><span class=3D"=
mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DEigenvalues_and_eigenvectors&am=
p;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D4" title=3D"Edit section: Eigenvalues and eig=
envectors of matrices"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-b=
racket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
See also: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_vector" title=
=3D"Euclidean vector">Euclidean vector</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Matrix_(mathematics)" title=3D"Matrix (mathematics)">Matrix (m=
athematics)</a></div>
<p>Eigenvalues and eigenvectors are often introduced to students in the con=
text of linear algebra courses focused on matrices.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Corn=
ellMathCourses_25-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Eigenvalues_and_eigenvectors#cite_note-CornellMathCourses-25"><span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>22<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a><=
/sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-UMichMathCourses_26-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eigenvalues_and_eigenvectors#cite_note-UM=
ichMathCourses-26"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>23<span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
Furthermore, linear transformations over a finite-dimensional vector space =
can be represented using matrices,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEHerstein19642=
28,_229_3-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/E=
igenvalues_and_eigenvectors#cite_note-FOOTNOTEHerstein1964228,_229-3"><span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a><=
/sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTENering197038_4-1" class=3D"reference"><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eigenvalues_and_eigenvectors#cite_note=
-FOOTNOTENering197038-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> which is especially common in numerica=
l and computational applications.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEPressTeukolsky=
VetterlingFlannery200738_27-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Eigenvalues_and_eigenvectors#cite_note-FOOTNOTEPressTeukol=
skyVetterlingFlannery200738-27"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>24<spa=
n class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<figure class=3D"mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Eigenvalue_equation.svg" class=3D"mw-file-des=
cription"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/=
