able>
<p>Using the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Leibniz_formula_for_d=
eterminants" title=3D"Leibniz formula for determinants">Leibniz formula for=
 determinants</a>, the left-hand side of equation (<b><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eigenvalues_and_eigenvectors#math_3">3</a></b>) is a <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polynomial" title=3D"Polynomial">pol=
ynomial</a> function of the variable <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"=
font-style:italic;">=CE=BB</span> and the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Degree_of_a_polynomial" title=3D"Degree of a polynomial">degree</a>=
 of this polynomial is <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:ita=
lic;">n</span>, the order of the matrix <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=
=3D"font-style:italic;">A</span>. Its <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Coefficient" title=3D"Coefficient">coefficients</a> depend on the entri=
es of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">A</span>, e=
xcept that its term of degree <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-st=
yle:italic;">n</span> is always <span class=3D"texhtml">(=E2=88=921)<sup><i=
>n</i></sup><i>=CE=BB</i><sup><i>n</i></sup></span>. This polynomial is cal=
led the <i>characteristic polynomial</i> of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" st=
yle=3D"font-style:italic;">A</span>. Equation (<b><a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Eigenvalues_and_eigenvectors#math_3">3</a></b>) is called t=
he <i>characteristic equation</i> or the <i>secular equation</i> of <span c=
lass=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">A</span>.
</p><p>The characteristic polynomial of an <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" sty=
le=3D"font-style:italic;">n</span>-by-<span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D=
"font-style:italic;">n</span> matrix <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"=
font-style:italic;">A</span>, being a polynomial of degree <span class=3D"t=
exhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">n</span>, has at most <span class=
=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">n</span> <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Complex_number" title=3D"Complex number">complex numb=
er</a> roots, which can be found by factoring the characteristic polynomial=
, or numerically by root finding.  The characteristic polynomial can be <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Factorization" title=3D"Factorization=
">factored</a> into the product of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"fo=
nt-style:italic;">n</span> linear terms,
</p>
