-image-display mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertica=
l-align: -2.505ex; width:30.15ex; height:6.176ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle \m=
athbf {v} _{\lambda =3D1}=3D{\begin{bmatrix}1\\-1\end{bmatrix}},\quad \math=
bf {v} _{\lambda =3D3}=3D{\begin{bmatrix}1\\1\end{bmatrix}}.}"></span>
</p><p>If the entries of the matrix <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"f=
ont-style:italic;">A</span> are all real numbers, then the coefficients of =
the characteristic polynomial will also be real numbers, but the eigenvalue=
s may still have nonzero imaginary parts. The entries of the corresponding =
eigenvectors therefore may also have nonzero imaginary parts. Similarly, th=
e eigenvalues may be <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Irrational_nu=
mber" title=3D"Irrational number">irrational numbers</a> even if all the en=
tries of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">A</span>=
 are <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rational_number" title=3D"Rat=
ional number">rational numbers</a> or even if they are all integers. Howeve=
r, if the entries of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:itali=
c;">A</span> are all <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Algebraic_num=
ber" title=3D"Algebraic number">algebraic numbers</a>, which include the ra=
tionals, the eigenvalues must also be algebraic numbers.
</p><p>The non-real roots of a real polynomial with real coefficients can b=
e grouped into pairs of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Complex_co=
njugate" title=3D"Complex conjugate">complex conjugates</a>, namely with th=
e two members of each pair having imaginary parts that differ only in sign =
and the same real part. If the degree is odd, then by the <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Intermediate_value_theorem" title=3D"Intermediate v=
alue theorem">intermediate value theorem</a> at least one of the roots is r=
eal. Therefore, any <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Real_matrix" c=
lass=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Real matrix">real matrix</a> with odd order h=
as at least one real eigenvalue, whereas a real matrix with even order may =
not have any real eigenvalues. The eigenvectors associated with these compl=
ex eigenvalues are also complex and also appear in complex conjugate pairs.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Spectrum_of_a_matrix">Spect=
rum of a matrix</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editse=
ction-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?titl=
e=3DEigenvalues_and_eigenvectors&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D6" title=
=3D"Edit section: Spectrum of a matrix"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D=
"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The <b><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spectrum_of_a_matrix" ti=
tle=3D"Spectrum of a matrix">spectrum</a></b> of a matrix is the list of ei=
genvalues, repeated according to multiplicity; in an alternative notation t=
he set of eigenvalues with their multiplicities.
</p><p>An important quantity associated with the spectrum is the maximum ab=
solute value of any eigenvalue.  This is known as the <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spectral_radius#Matrices" title=3D"Spectral radius">spe=
ctral radius</a> of the matrix.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Algebraic_multiplicity">Alg=
ebraic multiplicity</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-ed=
itsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?=
title=3DEigenvalues_and_eigenvectors&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D7" tit=
le=3D"Edit section: Algebraic multiplicity"><span>edit</span></a><span clas=
s=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Let <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>=CE=BB</i><sub><i>i</i></sub></span> be a=
n eigenvalue of an <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;=
">n</span>-by-<span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">n</=
span> matrix <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">A</s=
pan>. The <b>algebraic multiplicity</b> <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>=CE=BC</=
i><sub><i>A</i></sub>(<i>=CE=BB</i><sub><i>i</i></sub>)</span> of the eigen=
value is its <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multiple_roots_of_a_p=
olynomial" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Multiple roots of a polynomial">m=
ultiplicity as a root</a> of the characteristic polynomial, that is, the la=
rgest integer <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">k</=
span> such that <span class=3D"texhtml">(<i>=CE=BB</i> =E2=88=92 <i>=CE=BB<=
/i><sub><i>i</i></sub>)<sup><i>k</i></sup></span> <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
