n></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
See also: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Left_and_right_(algebra)=
" title=3D"Left and right (algebra)">left and right (algebra)</a></div>
<p>Many disciplines traditionally represent vectors as matrices with a sing=
le column rather than as matrices with a single row. For that reason, the w=
ord "eigenvector" in the context of matrices almost always refers to a <b><=
dfn>right eigenvector</dfn></b>, namely a <em>column</em> vector that <em>r=
ight</em> multiplies the <span class=3D"nowrap"><span data-sort-value=3D"&n=
bsp;!"><span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">n</span>=
=E2=80=89=C3=97=E2=80=89<span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:it=
alic;">n</span></span></span> matrix <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"=
font-style:italic;">A</span> in the defining equation, equation (<b><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eigenvalues_and_eigenvectors#math_1">1</a=
></b>),
<span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-block"><span class=3D"mwe-=
math-mathml-display mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math di=
splay=3D"block" xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\d=
isplaystyle A\mathbf {v} =3D\lambda \mathbf {v} .}">
