l-align: -0.671ex; width:13.111ex; height:3.009ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle Q=
^{-1}AQ=3D\Lambda .}"></span>
</p><p><span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">A</span> c=
an therefore be decomposed into a matrix composed of its eigenvectors, a di=
agonal matrix with its eigenvalues along the diagonal, and the inverse of t=
he matrix of eigenvectors. This is called the <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Eigendecomposition" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Eigendecompo=
sition">eigendecomposition</a> and it is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Matrix_similarity" title=3D"Matrix similarity">similarity transfor=
mation</a>. Such a matrix <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:=
italic;">A</span> is said to be <i><dfn>similar</dfn></i> to the diagonal m=
atrix <span class=3D"texhtml">=CE=9B</span> or <i><a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Diagonalizable" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Diagonalizab=
le">diagonalizable</a></i>. The matrix <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=
=3D"font-style:italic;">Q</span> is the change of basis matrix of the simil=
arity transformation. Essentially, the matrices <span class=3D"texhtml mvar=
" style=3D"font-style:italic;">A</span> and <span class=3D"texhtml">=CE=9B<=
/span> represent the same linear transformation expressed in two different =
bases. The eigenvectors are used as the basis when representing the linear =
transformation as&nbsp;<span class=3D"texhtml">=CE=9B</span>.
</p><p>Conversely, suppose a matrix <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"f=
ont-style:italic;">A</span> is diagonalizable. Let <span class=3D"texhtml m=
var" style=3D"font-style:italic;">P</span> be a non-singular square matrix =
such that <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>P</i><span style=3D"padding-left:0.12e=
m;"><sup>=E2=88=921</sup></span><i>AP</i></span> is some diagonal matrix <s=
pan class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">D</span>. Left mult=
iplying both by <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">P=
</span>, <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>AP</i> =3D <i>PD</i></span>. Each colum=
n of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">P</span> mus=
t therefore be an eigenvector of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font=
-style:italic;">A</span> whose eigenvalue is the corresponding diagonal ele=
ment of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">D</span>.=
 Since the columns of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:ital=
ic;">P</span> must be linearly independent for <span class=3D"texhtml mvar"=
 style=3D"font-style:italic;">P</span> to be invertible, there exist <span =
class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">n</span> linearly indep=
endent eigenvectors of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:ita=
lic;">A</span>. It then follows that the eigenvectors of <span class=3D"tex=
html mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">A</span> form a basis if and only i=
f <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">A</span> is dia=
gonalizable.
</p><p>A matrix that is not diagonalizable is said to be <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Defective_matrix" title=3D"Defective matrix">defecti=
ve</a>. For defective matrices, the notion of eigenvectors generalizes to <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Generalized_eigenvector" title=3D"G=
eneralized eigenvector">generalized eigenvectors</a> and the diagonal matri=
x of eigenvalues generalizes to the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Jordan_normal_form" title=3D"Jordan normal form">Jordan normal form</a>. =
Over an algebraically closed field, any matrix <span class=3D"texhtml mvar"=
 style=3D"font-style:italic;">A</span> has a Jordan normal form and therefo=
re admits a basis of generalized eigenvectors and a decomposition into <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Generalized_eigenspace" class=3D"mw-re=
direct" title=3D"Generalized eigenspace">generalized eigenspaces</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Variational_characterizatio=
n">Variational characterization</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span cl=
ass=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
w/index.php?title=3DEigenvalues_and_eigenvectors&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;sect=
ion=3D12" title=3D"Edit section: Variational characterization"><span>edit</=
span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Min-max_theorem" tit=
le=3D"Min-max theorem">Min-max theorem</a></div>
<p>In the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hermitian_matrix" title=
=3D"Hermitian matrix">Hermitian</a> case, eigenvalues can be given a variat=
ional characterization. The largest eigenvalue of <span class=3D"texhtml mv=
ar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">H</span> is the maximum value of the <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quadratic_form" title=3D"Quadratic form=
">quadratic form</a> <span class=3D"texhtml"><span style=3D"white-space:now=
rap"><b>x</b><sup>T</sup><span style=3D"padding-right:0.15em;"><i>H</i></sp=
an><b>x</b><span style=3D"margin-left:0.25em">/</span><span style=3D"margin=
-left:0.25em"><b>x</b><sup>T</sup><b>x</b></span></span></span>. A value of=
 <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>x</b></span> that realizes that maximum is an e=
igenvector.
</p>
