re a linear subspace of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:it=
alic;">V</span>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTENering1970107Shilov1977109_43-0=
" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eigenvalues_=
and_eigenvectors#cite_note-FOOTNOTENering1970107Shilov1977109-43"><span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>40<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></su=
p> If that subspace has dimension 1, it is sometimes called an <b><dfn>eige=
nline</dfn></b>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTELipschutzLipson2002111_44-0" cl=
ass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eigenvalues_and_=
eigenvectors#cite_note-FOOTNOTELipschutzLipson2002111-44"><span class=3D"ci=
te-bracket">[</span>41<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The <b><dfn>geometric multiplicity</dfn></b> <span class=3D"texhtml"=
><i>=CE=B3</i><sub><i>T</i></sub>(<i>=CE=BB</i>)</span> of an eigenvalue <s=
pan class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">=CE=BB</span> is th=
e dimension of the eigenspace associated with <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" =
style=3D"font-style:italic;">=CE=BB</span>, i.e., the maximum number of lin=
early independent eigenvectors associated with that eigenvalue.<sup id=3D"c=
ite_ref-FOOTNOTENering1970107GolubVan_Loan1996316Roman2008p._189_=C2=A78_45=
-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eigenvalue=
s_and_eigenvectors#cite_note-FOOTNOTENering1970107GolubVan_Loan1996316Roman=
2008p._189_%C2%A78-45"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>42<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> By the definition of eigenvalues and e=
igenvectors, <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>=CE=B3</i><sub><i>T</i></sub>(<i>=
=CE=BB</i>) =E2=89=A5 1</span> because every eigenvalue has at least one ei=
genvector.
</p><p>The eigenspaces of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:=
italic;">T</span> always form a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Di=
rect_sum" title=3D"Direct sum">direct sum</a>. As a consequence, eigenvecto=
rs of <em>different</em> eigenvalues are always linearly independent. There=
fore, the sum of the dimensions of the eigenspaces cannot exceed the dimens=
ion <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">n</span> of t=
he vector space on which <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:i=
talic;">T</span> operates, and there cannot be more than <span class=3D"tex=
html mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">n</span> distinct eigenvalues.<sup =
id=3D"cite_ref-46" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Eigenvalues_and_eigenvectors#cite_note-46"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">[</span>d<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Any subspace spanned by eigenvectors of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar"=
 style=3D"font-style:italic;">T</span> is an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Invariant_subspace" title=3D"Invariant subspace">invariant subsp=
ace</a> of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">T</spa=
n>, and the restriction of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style=
:italic;">T</span> to such a subspace is diagonalizable. Moreover, if the e=
ntire vector space <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;=
">V</span> can be spanned by the eigenvectors of <span class=3D"texhtml mva=
r" style=3D"font-style:italic;">T</span>, or equivalently if the direct sum=
 of the eigenspaces associated with all the eigenvalues of <span class=3D"t=
exhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">T</span> is the entire vector spa=
ce <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">V</span>, then=
 a basis of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">V</sp=
an> called an <b><dfn>eigenbasis</dfn></b> can be formed from linearly inde=
pendent eigenvectors of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:it=
alic;">T</span>. When <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:ital=
ic;">T</span> admits an eigenbasis, <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"f=
ont-style:italic;">T</span> is diagonalizable.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Spectral_theory">Spectral t=
heory</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-brac=
ket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DEigenv=
alues_and_eigenvectors&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D25" title=3D"Edit se=
ction: Spectral theory"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-=
bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spectral_theory" tit=
le=3D"Spectral theory">Spectral theory</a></div>
<p>If <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">=CE=BB</spa=
n> is an eigenvalue of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:ita=
lic;">T</span>, then the operator <span class=3D"texhtml">(<i>T</i> =E2=88=
=92 <i>=CE=BBI</i>)</span> is not <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
One_to_one_correspondence" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"One to one corres=
pondence">one-to-one</a>, and therefore its inverse <span class=3D"texhtml"=
>(<i>T</i> =E2=88=92 <i>=CE=BBI</i>)<sup>=E2=88=921</sup></span> does not e=
xist. The converse is true for finite-dimensional vector spaces, but not fo=
r infinite-dimensional vector spaces. In general, the operator <span class=
=3D"texhtml">(<i>T</i> =E2=88=92 <i>=CE=BBI</i>)</span> may not have an inv=
erse even if <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">=CE=
=BB</span> is not an eigenvalue.
</p><p>For this reason, in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Functio=
nal_analysis" title=3D"Functional analysis">functional analysis</a> eigenva=
lues can be generalized to the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spe=
ctrum_(functional_analysis)" title=3D"Spectrum (functional analysis)">spect=
rum of a linear operator</a> <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-sty=
le:italic;">T</span> as the set of all scalars <span class=3D"texhtml mvar"=
 style=3D"font-style:italic;">=CE=BB</span> for which the operator <span cl=
ass=3D"texhtml">(<i>T</i> =E2=88=92 <i>=CE=BBI</i>)</span> has no <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bounded_operator" title=3D"Bounded operat=
or">bounded</a> inverse. The spectrum of an operator always contains all it=
s eigenvalues but is not limited to them.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Associative_algebras_and_re=
presentation_theory">Associative algebras and representation theory</h3><sp=
an class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span>=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DEigenvalues_and_eig=
envectors&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D26" title=3D"Edit section: Associ=
ative algebras and representation theory"><span>edit</span></a><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Weight_(representati=
on_theory)" title=3D"Weight (representation theory)">Weight (representation=
 theory)</a></div>
<p>One can generalize the algebraic object that is acting on the vector spa=
ce, replacing a single operator acting on a vector space with an <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Algebra_representation" title=3D"Algebra rep=
resentation">algebra representation</a>&nbsp;=E2=80=93  an <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Associative_algebra" title=3D"Associative algebra"=
>associative algebra</a> acting on a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Module_(mathematics)" title=3D"Module (mathematics)">module</a>. The stu=
dy of such actions is the field of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Representation_theory" title=3D"Representation theory">representation theo=
ry</a>.
</p><p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Weight_(representation_=
theory)" title=3D"Weight (representation theory)">representation-theoretica=
l concept of weight</a> is an analog of eigenvalues, while <i>weight vector=
s</i> and <i>weight spaces</i> are the analogs of eigenvectors and eigenspa=
ces, respectively.
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hecke_eigensheaf" title=3D"=
Hecke eigensheaf">Hecke eigensheaf</a> is a tensor-multiple of itself and i=
s considered in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Langlands_correspo=
ndence" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Langlands correspondence">Langlands =
correspondence</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Dynamic_equations">Dynamic =
