<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Calculation">Calculation</h=
2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</=
span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DEigenvalues_an=
d_eigenvectors&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D28" title=3D"Edit section: C=
alculation"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</=
span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eigenvalue_algorithm=
" title=3D"Eigenvalue algorithm">Eigenvalue algorithm</a></div>
<p>The calculation of eigenvalues and eigenvectors is a topic where theory,=
 as presented in elementary linear algebra textbooks, is often very far fro=
m practice.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Classical_method">Classical=
 method</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-br=
acket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DEige=
nvalues_and_eigenvectors&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D29" title=3D"Edit =
section: Classical method"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsecti=
on-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The classical method is to first find the eigenvalues, and then calculat=
e the eigenvectors for each eigenvalue. It is in several ways poorly suited=
 for non-exact arithmetics such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Floating-point" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Floating-point">floating-po=
int</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Eigenvalues">Eigenvalues</h=
4><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</=
span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DEigenvalues_an=
d_eigenvectors&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D30" title=3D"Edit section: E=
igenvalues"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</=
span></span></div>
<p>The eigenvalues of a matrix <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-s=
tyle:italic;">A</span> can be determined by finding the roots of the charac=
teristic polynomial. This is easy for <span class=3D"nowrap"><span data-sor=
t-value=3D"4&nbsp;!">2=E2=80=89=C3=97=E2=80=892</span></span> matrices, but=
 the difficulty increases rapidly with the size of the matrix.
</p><p>In theory, the coefficients of the characteristic polynomial can be =
computed exactly, since they are sums of products of matrix elements; and t=
here are algorithms that can find all the roots of a polynomial of arbitrar=
y degree to any required <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Accuracy"=
 class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Accuracy">accuracy</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-=
FOOTNOTETrefethenBau1997_47-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Eigenvalues_and_eigenvectors#cite_note-FOOTNOTETrefethenBa=
u1997-47"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>43<span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">]</span></a></sup> However, this approach is not viable in practice beca=
use the coefficients would be contaminated by unavoidable <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Round-off_error" title=3D"Round-off error">round-of=
f errors</a>, and the roots of a polynomial can be an extremely sensitive f=
unction of the coefficients (as exemplified by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Wilkinson%27s_polynomial" title=3D"Wilkinson's polynomial">Wil=
kinson's polynomial</a>).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTETrefethenBau1997_47-1"=
 class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eigenvalues_a=
nd_eigenvectors#cite_note-FOOTNOTETrefethenBau1997-47"><span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">[</span>43<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Even for=
 matrices whose elements are integers the calculation becomes nontrivial, b=
ecause the sums are very long; the constant term is the <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Determinant" title=3D"Determinant">determinant</a>, w=
hich for an <span class=3D"nowrap"><span data-sort-value=3D"&nbsp;!"><span =
class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">n</span>=E2=80=89=C3=97=
=E2=80=89<span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">n</span>=
</span></span> matrix is a sum of <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>n</i>!</span> =
different products.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-48" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eigenvalues_and_eigenvectors#cite_note-48"><sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>e<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a=
></sup>
</p><p>Explicit <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Algebraic_solution=
" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Algebraic solution">algebraic formulas</a>=
 for the roots of a polynomial exist only if the degree <span class=3D"texh=
tml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">n</span> is 4 or less. According to =
the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Abel%E2%80%93Ruffini_theorem" =
title=3D"Abel=E2=80=93Ruffini theorem">Abel=E2=80=93Ruffini theorem</a> the=
re is no general, explicit and exact algebraic formula for the roots of a p=
olynomial with degree 5 or more. (Generality matters because any polynomial=
 with degree <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">n</s=
pan> is the characteristic polynomial of some <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Companion_matrix" title=3D"Companion matrix">companion matrix</=
a> of order <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">n</sp=
an>.) Therefore, for matrices of order 5 or more, the eigenvalues and eigen=
vectors cannot be obtained by an explicit algebraic formula, and must there=
fore be computed by approximate <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nu=
merical_method" title=3D"Numerical method">numerical methods</a>. Even the =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cubic_function#General_solution_to=
_the_cubic_equation_with_real_coefficients" title=3D"Cubic function">exact =
formula</a> for the roots of a degree 3 polynomial is numerically impractic=
al.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading4"><h4 id=3D"Eigenvectors">Eigenvectors<=
/h4><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[=
</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DEigenvalues_=
and_eigenvectors&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D31" title=3D"Edit section:=
 Eigenvectors"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">=
]</span></span></div>
<p>Once the (exact) value of an eigenvalue is known, the corresponding eige=
nvectors can be found by finding nonzero solutions of the eigenvalue equati=
on, that becomes a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_system" =
title=3D"Linear system">system of linear equations</a> with known coefficie=
nts. For example, once it is known that 6 is an eigenvalue of the matrix
<span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-block"><span class=3D"mwe-=
math-mathml-display mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math di=
splay=3D"block" xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\d=
isplaystyle A=3D{\begin{bmatrix}4&amp;1\\6&amp;3\end{bmatrix}}}">
