</p><p>Both equations reduce to the single linear equation <span class=3D"t=
exhtml"><i>y</i> =3D 2<i>x</i></span>. Therefore, any vector of the form <s=
pan class=3D"texhtml">[<i>a</i>&nbsp; 2<i>a</i>]<sup>T</sup></span>, for an=
y nonzero real number <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:ital=
ic;">a</span>, is an eigenvector of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"f=
ont-style:italic;">A</span> with eigenvalue <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>=CE=
=BB</i> =3D 6</span>.
</p><p>The matrix <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;"=
>A</span> above has another eigenvalue <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>=CE=BB</i=
> =3D 1</span>. A similar calculation shows that the corresponding eigenvec=
tors are the nonzero solutions of <span class=3D"texhtml">3<i>x</i> + <i>y<=
/i> =3D 0</span>, that is, any vector of the form <span class=3D"texhtml">[=
<i>b</i>&nbsp; =E2=88=923<i>b</i>]<sup>T</sup></span>, for any nonzero real=
 number <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">b</span>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Simple_iterative_methods">S=
imple iterative methods</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"m=
w-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.=
php?title=3DEigenvalues_and_eigenvectors&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D32=
" title=3D"Edit section: Simple iterative methods"><span>edit</span></a><sp=
an class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Power_iteration" tit=
le=3D"Power iteration">Power iteration</a></div>
<p>The converse approach, of first seeking the eigenvectors and then determ=
ining each eigenvalue from its eigenvector, turns out to be far more tracta=
ble for computers. The easiest algorithm here consists of picking an arbitr=
ary starting vector and then repeatedly multiplying it with the matrix (opt=
ionally normalizing the vector to keep its elements of reasonable size); th=
is makes the vector converge towards an eigenvector. <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Inverse_iteration" title=3D"Inverse iteration">A variati=
on</a> is to instead multiply the vector by <span class=3D"texhtml">(<i>A</=
