<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Modern_methods">Modern meth=
ods</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracke=
t">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DEigenval=
ues_and_eigenvectors&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D33" title=3D"Edit sect=
ion: Modern methods"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bra=
cket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Efficient, accurate methods to compute eigenvalues and eigenvectors of a=
rbitrary matrices were not known until the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/QR_algorithm" title=3D"QR algorithm">QR algorithm</a> was designed=
 in 1961.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTETrefethenBau1997_47-2" class=3D"refere=
nce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eigenvalues_and_eigenvectors#=
cite_note-FOOTNOTETrefethenBau1997-47"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span=
>43<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Combining the <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Householder_transformation" title=3D"Househo=
lder transformation">Householder transformation</a> with the LU decompositi=
on results in an algorithm with better convergence than the QR algorithm.<s=
up class=3D"noprint Inline-Template Template-Fact" style=3D"white-space:now=
rap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_neede=
d" title=3D"Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title=3D"This claim needs refe=
rences to reliable sources. (March 2013)">citation needed</span></a></i>]</=
sup> For large <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hermitian_matrix" t=
itle=3D"Hermitian matrix">Hermitian</a> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Sparse_matrix" title=3D"Sparse matrix">sparse matrices</a>, the <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lanczos_algorithm" title=3D"Lanczos alg=
orithm">Lanczos algorithm</a> is one example of an efficient <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Iterative_method" title=3D"Iterative method">ite=
rative method</a> to compute eigenvalues and eigenvectors, among several ot=
her possibilities.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTETrefethenBau1997_47-3" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eigenvalues_and_eig=
envectors#cite_note-FOOTNOTETrefethenBau1997-47"><span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">[</span>43<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Most numeric methods that compute the eigenvalues of a matrix also d=
etermine a set of corresponding eigenvectors as a by-product of the computa=
tion, although sometimes implementors choose to discard the eigenvector inf=
ormation as soon as it is no longer needed.
</p>
