<p>The characteristic equation for a rotation is a <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Quadratic_equation" title=3D"Quadratic equation">quadratic=
 equation</a> with <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Discriminant" t=
itle=3D"Discriminant">discriminant</a> <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>D</i> =3D=
 =E2=88=924(sin <i>=CE=B8</i>)<sup>2</sup></span>, which is a negative numb=
er whenever <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">=CE=
=B8</span> is not an integer multiple of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=
=3D"font-style:italic;">=CF=80</span> (180=C2=B0). Therefore, except for th=
ese special cases, the two eigenvalues are complex numbers, <span class=3D"=
texhtml">cos <i>=CE=B8</i> =C2=B1 <span style=3D"padding-right:0.15em;"><i>=
i</i></span>sin <i>=CE=B8</i></span>; and all eigenvectors have non-real en=
tries. Indeed, except for those special cases, a rotation changes the direc=
tion of every nonzero vector in the plane.
</p><p>A linear transformation that takes a square to a rectangle of the sa=
me area (a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Squeeze_mapping" title=
=3D"Squeeze mapping">squeeze mapping</a>) has reciprocal eigenvalues.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Principal_component_analysi=
s">Principal component analysis</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span cl=
ass=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
w/index.php?title=3DEigenvalues_and_eigenvectors&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;sect=
ion=3D36" title=3D"Edit section: Principal component analysis"><span>edit</=
span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:GaussianScatterPCA.png" class=
=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia=
/commons/thumb/1/15/GaussianScatterPCA.png/250px-GaussianScatterPCA.png" de=
coding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"235" class=3D"mw-file-element" dat=
a-file-width=3D"1152" data-file-height=3D"1081"></a><figcaption>PCA of the =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multivariate_Gaussian_distribution=
" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Multivariate Gaussian distribution">multiv=
ariate Gaussian distribution</a> centered at <span class=3D"texhtml">(1, 3)=
</span> with a standard deviation of <span class=3D"texhtml">3</span> in ro=
ughly the <span class=3D"texhtml">(0.878, 0.478)</span> direction and of&nb=
sp;<span class=3D"texhtml">1</span> in the orthogonal direction. The vector=
s shown are unit eigenvectors of the (symmetric, positive-semidefinite) <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Covariance_matrix" title=3D"Covarianc=
e matrix">covariance matrix</a> scaled by the square root of the correspond=
ing eigenvalue. Just as in the one-dimensional case, the square root is tak=
en because the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Standard_deviation"=
 title=3D"Standard deviation">standard deviation</a> is more readily visual=
ized than the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Variance" title=3D"V=
ariance">variance</a>.</figcaption></figure>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Principal_component_=
analysis" title=3D"Principal component analysis">Principal component analys=
is</a></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
See also: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Positive_semidefinite_ma=
trix" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Positive semidefinite matrix">Positive=
 semidefinite matrix</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Facto=
r_analysis" title=3D"Factor analysis">Factor analysis</a></div>
<p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eigendecomposition_of_a_mat=
rix#Real_symmetric_matrices" title=3D"Eigendecomposition of a matrix">eigen=
decomposition</a> of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Symmetric_m=
atrix" title=3D"Symmetric matrix">symmetric</a> <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Positive_semidefinite_matrix" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"=
Positive semidefinite matrix">positive semidefinite</a> (PSD) <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Positive_semidefinite_matrix" class=3D"mw-redir=
ect" title=3D"Positive semidefinite matrix">matrix</a> yields an <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orthogonal_basis" title=3D"Orthogonal basis"=
>orthogonal basis</a> of eigenvectors, each of which has a nonnegative eige=
nvalue. The orthogonal decomposition of a PSD matrix is used in <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multivariate_statistics" title=3D"Multivariat=
e statistics">multivariate analysis</a>, where the <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Sample_variance" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Sample var=
iance">sample</a> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Covariance_matri=
x" title=3D"Covariance matrix">covariance matrices</a> are PSD. This orthog=
onal decomposition is called <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Princ=
ipal_component_analysis" title=3D"Principal component analysis">principal c=
omponent analysis</a> (PCA) in statistics. PCA studies <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_relation" title=3D"Linear relation">linear rela=
tions</a> among variables. PCA is performed on the <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Covariance_matrix" title=3D"Covariance matrix">covariance =
matrix</a> or the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Correlation_matr=
ix" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Correlation matrix">correlation matrix</=
a> (in which each variable is scaled to have its <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Sample_variance" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Sample varia=
nce">sample variance</a> equal to one). For the covariance or correlation m=
atrix, the eigenvectors correspond to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Principal_component_analysis" title=3D"Principal component analysis">pr=
incipal components</a> and the eigenvalues to the <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Explained_variance" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Explaine=
d variance">variance explained</a> by the principal components. Principal c=
omponent analysis of the correlation matrix provides an <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orthogonal_basis" title=3D"Orthogonal basis">orthogon=
al basis</a> for the space of the observed data: In this basis, the largest=
 eigenvalues correspond to the principal components that are associated wit=
h most of the covariability among a number of observed data.
</p><p>Principal component analysis is used as a means of <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dimensionality_reduction" title=3D"Dimensionality r=
eduction">dimensionality reduction</a> in the study of large <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Data_set" title=3D"Data set">data sets</a>, such=
 as those encountered in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bioinform=
atics" title=3D"Bioinformatics">bioinformatics</a>. In <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Q_methodology" title=3D"Q methodology">Q methodology</=
a>, the eigenvalues of the correlation matrix determine the Q-methodologist=
's judgment of <em>practical</em> significance (which differs from the <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistical_significance" title=3D"Sta=
tistical significance">statistical significance</a> of <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hypothesis_testing" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Hyp=
othesis testing">hypothesis testing</a>; cf. <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Scree%27s_test" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Scree's test">cri=
teria for determining the number of factors</a>). More generally, principal=
 component analysis can be used as a method of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Factor_analysis" title=3D"Factor analysis">factor analysis</a>=
 in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Structural_equation_model" cla=
ss=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Structural equation model">structural equation =
modeling</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Graphs">Graphs</h3><span cl=
ass=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DEigenvalues_and_eigenvec=
tors&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D37" title=3D"Edit section: Graphs"><sp=
an>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></d=
iv>
<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spectral_graph_theory" title=
=3D"Spectral graph theory">spectral graph theory</a>, an eigenvalue of a <a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Graph_theory" title=3D"Graph theory"=
>graph</a> is defined as an eigenvalue of the graph's <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Adjacency_matrix" title=3D"Adjacency matrix">adjacency =
matrix</a> <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">A</spa=
n>, or (increasingly) of the graph's <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Laplacian_matrix" title=3D"Laplacian matrix">Laplacian matrix</a> due to=
 its <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Discrete_Laplace_operator" ti=
tle=3D"Discrete Laplace operator">discrete Laplace operator</a>, which is e=
ither <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>D</i> =E2=88=92 <i>A</i></span> (sometimes=
 called the <i><dfn>combinatorial Laplacian</dfn></i>) or <span class=3D"te=
xhtml"><i>I</i> =E2=88=92 <i>D</i><sup>=E2=88=921/2</sup><i>AD</i><sup>=E2=
=88=921/2</sup></span> (sometimes called the <i><dfn>normalized Laplacian</=
dfn></i>), where <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">=
D</span> is a diagonal matrix with <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"fo=
nt-style:italic;">D<sub>ii</sub></span> equal to the degree of vertex <span=
 class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">v<sub>i</sub></span>, =
and in <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>D</i><sup>=E2=88=921/2</sup></span>, the =
<span class=3D"texhtml"><span style=3D"padding-right:0.15em;"><i>i</i></spa=
n></span>-th diagonal entry is <span class=3D"nowrap"><span class=3D"mwe-ma=
th-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline m=
we-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.=
org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\textstyle 1/{\sqrt {\deg(v_{i})}}}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"false" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mn>1</mn>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mo>/</mo>
        </mrow>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <msqrt>
            <mi>deg</mi>
            <mo>=E2=81=A1<!-- =E2=81=A1 --></mo>
            <mo stretchy=3D"false">(</mo>
            <msub>
              <mi>v</mi>
              <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                <mi>i</mi>
              </mrow>
            </msub>
            <mo stretchy=3D"false">)</mo>
          </msqrt>
        </mrow>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\textstyle 1/{\sqrt {\deg(v=
_{i})}}}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/c3cd68f11bd7f7cbe229f0ef39a9e37a0d7b67fd" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -1.005ex; width:11.873ex; height:3.343ex;" alt=3D"{\textstyle 1/{\s=
qrt {\deg(v_{i})}}}"></span>.</span> The <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=
=3D"font-style:italic;">k</span>-th principal eigenvector of a graph is def=
ined as either the eigenvector corresponding to the <span class=3D"texhtml =
mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">k</span>-th largest or <span class=3D"te=
xhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">k</span>-th smallest eigenvalue of=
 the Laplacian. The first principal eigenvector of the graph is also referr=
ed to merely as the principal eigenvector.
</p><p>The principal eigenvector is used to measure the <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eigenvector_centrality" title=3D"Eigenvector centrali=
ty">centrality</a> of its vertices. An example is <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Google" title=3D"Google">Google</a>'s <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/PageRank" title=3D"PageRank">PageRank</a> algorithm. Th=
e principal eigenvector of a modified <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Adjacency_matrix" title=3D"Adjacency matrix">adjacency matrix</a> of th=
e World Wide Web graph gives the page ranks as its components. This vector =
corresponds to the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stationary_dist=
ribution" title=3D"Stationary distribution">stationary distribution</a> of =
the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Markov_chain" title=3D"Markov =
chain">Markov chain</a> represented by the row-normalized adjacency matrix;=
 however, the adjacency matrix must first be modified to ensure a stationar=
y distribution exists. The second smallest eigenvector can be used to parti=
tion the graph into clusters, via <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Spectral_clustering" title=3D"Spectral clustering">spectral clustering</a>.=
 Other methods are also available for clustering.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Markov_chains">Markov chain=
s</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket"=
>[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DEigenvalue=
s_and_eigenvectors&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D38" title=3D"Edit sectio=
n: Markov chains"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracke=
t">]</span></span></div>
<p>A <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Markov_chain" title=3D"Markov=
 chain">Markov chain</a> is represented by a matrix whose entries are the <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Transition_probabilities" class=3D"=
mw-redirect" title=3D"Transition probabilities">transition probabilities</a=
> between states of a system.  In particular the entries are non-negative, =
and every row of the matrix sums to one, being the sum of probabilities of =
transitions from one state to some other state of the system.  The <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Perron%E2%80%93Frobenius_theorem" title=
=3D"Perron=E2=80=93Frobenius theorem">Perron=E2=80=93Frobenius theorem</a> =
gives sufficient conditions for a Markov chain to have a unique dominant ei=
genvalue, which governs the convergence of the system to a steady state.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Vibration_analysis">Vibrati=
on analysis</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsectio=
n-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3D=
Eigenvalues_and_eigenvectors&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D39" title=3D"E=
dit section: Vibration analysis"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-edi=
tsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Mode_Shape_of_a_Tuning_Fork_at_Eigenfrequency=
_440.09_Hz.gif" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wi=
kimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/82/Mode_Shape_of_a_Tuning_Fork_at_Eig=
enfrequency_440.09_Hz.gif/250px-Mode_Shape_of_a_Tuning_Fork_at_Eigenfrequen=
cy_440.09_Hz.gif" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"234" class=3D"=
mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"656" data-file-height=3D"614"></a><figc=
aption>Mode shape of a tuning fork at eigenfrequency <span class=3D"nowrap"=
><span data-sort-value=3D"7002440090000000000=E2=99=A0"></span>440.09&nbsp;=
Hz</span></figcaption></figure>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vibration" title=3D"=
Vibration">Vibration</a></div>
<p>Eigenvalue problems occur naturally in the vibration analysis of mechani=
cal structures with many <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Degrees_o=
f_freedom_(mechanics)" title=3D"Degrees of freedom (mechanics)">degrees of =
freedom</a>. The eigenvalues are the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Natural_frequency" title=3D"Natural frequency">natural frequencies</a> (=
or <b><dfn>eigenfrequencies</dfn></b>) of vibration, and the eigenvectors a=
re the shapes of these vibrational modes. In particular, undamped vibration=
 is governed by
<span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-block"><span class=3D"mwe-=
math-mathml-display mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math di=
splay=3D"block" xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\d=
