            <mn>2</mn>
          </mrow>
        </msup>
        <mi>m</mi>
        <mi>x</mi>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle kx=3D\omega ^=
{2}mx}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/e74e3d27b717e9bfc94d5b4f3762d892bdc58d0f" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-display mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertica=
l-align: -0.338ex; width:11.51ex; height:2.676ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle kx=
=3D\omega ^{2}mx}"></span>
where <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>=CF=89</i><sup>2</sup></span> is the eigen=
value and <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">=CF=89<=
/span> is the (imaginary) <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Angular_=
frequency" title=3D"Angular frequency">angular frequency</a>. The principal=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vibration_mode" class=3D"mw-redir=
ect" title=3D"Vibration mode">vibration modes</a> are different from the pr=
incipal compliance modes, which are the eigenvectors of <span class=3D"texh=
tml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">k</span> alone. Furthermore, <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Damped_vibration" class=3D"mw-redirect" t=
itle=3D"Damped vibration">damped vibration</a>, governed by
<span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-block"><span class=3D"mwe-=
math-mathml-display mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math di=
splay=3D"block" xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\d=
isplaystyle m{\ddot {x}}+c{\dot {x}}+kx=3D0}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mi>m</mi>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mover>
              <mi>x</mi>
              <mo>=C2=A8<!-- =C2=A8 --></mo>
            </mover>
          </mrow>
        </mrow>
        <mo>+</mo>
        <mi>c</mi>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mover>
              <mi>x</mi>
              <mo>=CB=99<!-- =CB=99 --></mo>
            </mover>
          </mrow>
        </mrow>
        <mo>+</mo>
        <mi>k</mi>
        <mi>x</mi>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mn>0</mn>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle m{\ddot {x}}+=
c{\dot {x}}+kx=3D0}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/94204a6eb83dcdc6550e0f4cad8b127dab620f4f" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-display mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertica=
l-align: -0.505ex; width:18.189ex; height:2.343ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle m=
{\ddot {x}}+c{\dot {x}}+kx=3D0}"></span>
leads to a so-called <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quadratic_eig=
envalue_problem" title=3D"Quadratic eigenvalue problem">quadratic eigenvalu=
e problem</a>,
<span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-block"><span class=3D"mwe-=
math-mathml-display mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math di=
splay=3D"block" xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\d=
isplaystyle \left(\omega ^{2}m+\omega c+k\right)x=3D0.}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mrow>
          <mo>(</mo>
          <mrow>
            <msup>
              <mi>=CF=89<!-- =CF=89 --></mi>
              <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
                <mn>2</mn>
              </mrow>
            </msup>
            <mi>m</mi>
            <mo>+</mo>
            <mi>=CF=89<!-- =CF=89 --></mi>
            <mi>c</mi>
            <mo>+</mo>
            <mi>k</mi>
          </mrow>
          <mo>)</mo>
        </mrow>
        <mi>x</mi>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mn>0.</mn>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle \left(\omega =
^{2}m+\omega c+k\right)x=3D0.}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/e4ead2ed546c17096d1e8537e3d24c56c65db0e7" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-display mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertica=
l-align: -1.005ex; width:22.639ex; height:3.343ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle \=
left(\omega ^{2}m+\omega c+k\right)x=3D0.}"></span>
</p><p>This can be reduced to a generalized eigenvalue problem by <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quadratic_eigenvalue_problem#Methods_of_S=
olution" title=3D"Quadratic eigenvalue problem">algebraic manipulation</a> =
at the cost of solving a larger system.
</p><p>The orthogonality properties of the eigenvectors allows decoupling o=
f the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Differential_equation" title=
=3D"Differential equation">differential equations</a> so that the system ca=
n be represented as linear summation of the eigenvectors. The eigenvalue pr=
oblem of complex structures is often solved using <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Finite_element_analysis" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Fin=
ite element analysis">finite element analysis</a>, but neatly generalize th=
e solution to scalar-valued vibration problems.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Tensor_of_moment_of_inertia=
">Tensor of moment of inertia</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span clas=
s=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/=
index.php?title=3DEigenvalues_and_eigenvectors&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;sectio=
n=3D40" title=3D"Edit section: Tensor of moment of inertia"><span>edit</spa=
n></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mechanics" title=3D"Mechanic=
s">mechanics</a>, the eigenvectors of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Inertia_tensor" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Inertia tensor">mome=
nt of inertia tensor</a> define the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Principal_axis_(mechanics)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Principal axis=
 (mechanics)">principal axes</a> of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Rigid_body" title=3D"Rigid body">rigid body</a>. The <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tensor" title=3D"Tensor">tensor</a> of moment of <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Inertia" title=3D"Inertia">inertia</a=
> is a key quantity required to determine the rotation of a rigid body arou=
nd its <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Center_of_mass" title=3D"Ce=
nter of mass">center of mass</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Stress_tensor">Stress tenso=
r</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket"=
>[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DEigenvalue=
s_and_eigenvectors&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D41" title=3D"Edit sectio=
n: Stress tensor"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracke=
t">]</span></span></div>
<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Solid_mechanics" title=3D"So=
lid mechanics">solid mechanics</a>, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Stress_(mechanics)" title=3D"Stress (mechanics)">stress</a> tensor is=
 symmetric and so can be decomposed into a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Diagonal" title=3D"Diagonal">diagonal</a> tensor with the eigenval=
ues on the diagonal and eigenvectors as a basis. Because it is diagonal, in=
 this orientation, the stress tensor has no <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Shear_(mathematics)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Shear (mathem=
atics)">shear</a> components; the components it does have are the principal=
 components.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Schr=C3=B6dinger_equation">=
<span id=3D"Schr.C3.B6dinger_equation"></span>Schr=C3=B6dinger equation</h3=
><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</s=
pan><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DEigenvalues_and=
_eigenvectors&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D42" title=3D"Edit section: Sc=
hr=C3=B6dinger equation"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection=
-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/F=
ile:HAtomOrbitals.png" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://up=
load.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/cf/HAtomOrbitals.png/316px-HAt=
omOrbitals.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"271" height=3D"271" class=3D"mw=
-file-element" data-file-width=3D"316" data-file-height=3D"316"></a><figcap=
tion>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wavefunction" class=3D"mw=
-redirect" title=3D"Wavefunction">wavefunctions</a> associated with the <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bound_state" title=3D"Bound state">bo=
und states</a> of an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Electron" tit=
le=3D"Electron">electron</a> in a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Hydrogen_atom" title=3D"Hydrogen atom">hydrogen atom</a> can be seen as the=
 eigenvectors of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hydrogen_atom=
" title=3D"Hydrogen atom">hydrogen atom Hamiltonian</a> as well as of the <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Angular_momentum_operator" title=3D=
"Angular momentum operator">angular momentum operator</a>. They are associa=
ted with eigenvalues interpreted as their energies (increasing downward: <s=
pan class=3D"texhtml"><i>n</i> =3D 1, 2, 3, ...</span>) and <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Angular_momentum" title=3D"Angular momentum">angu=
lar momentum</a> (increasing across: s, p, d, ...). The illustration shows =
the square of the absolute value of the wavefunctions. Brighter areas corre=
spond to higher <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probability_densit=
y_function" title=3D"Probability density function">probability density</a> =
for a position <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Measurement_in_quan=
tum_mechanics" title=3D"Measurement in quantum mechanics">measurement</a>. =
The center of each figure is the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/A=
tomic_nucleus" title=3D"Atomic nucleus">atomic nucleus</a>, a <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Proton" title=3D"Proton">proton</a>.</figcaptio=
n></figure>
<p>An example of an eigenvalue equation where the transformation <span clas=
s=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">T</span> is represented in =
terms of a differential operator is the time-independent <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Schr%C3%B6dinger_equation" title=3D"Schr=C3=B6dinger=
 equation">Schr=C3=B6dinger equation</a> in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Quantum_mechanics" title=3D"Quantum mechanics">quantum mechanics<=
/a>:
<span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-block"><span class=3D"mwe-=
math-mathml-display mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math di=
splay=3D"block" xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\d=
isplaystyle H\psi _{E}=3DE\psi _{E}\,}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mi>H</mi>
        <msub>
          <mi>=CF=88<!-- =CF=88 --></mi>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mi>E</mi>
          </mrow>
        </msub>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mi>E</mi>
        <msub>
          <mi>=CF=88<!-- =CF=88 --></mi>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mi>E</mi>
          </mrow>
        </msub>
        <mspace width=3D"thinmathspace"></mspace>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle H\psi _{E}=3D=
E\psi _{E}\,}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/2bee1b56b8c500f5d904ad07ed6c310652d20098" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-display mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertica=
l-align: -0.671ex; width:13.327ex; height:2.509ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle H=
\psi _{E}=3DE\psi _{E}\,}"></span>
where the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hamiltonian_(quantum_mec=
hanics)" title=3D"Hamiltonian (quantum mechanics)">Hamiltonian</a> <span cl=
ass=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">H</span> is a second-orde=
r <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Differential_operator" title=3D"=
Differential operator">differential operator</a>, and the <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wavefunction" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Wavefu=
nction">wavefunction</a> <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:i=
talic;">=CF=88<sub>E</sub></span> is one of its eigenfunctions correspondin=
g to the eigenvalue <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic=
;">E</span>, interpreted as its <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/En=
ergy" title=3D"Energy">energy</a>.
</p><p>However, in the case where one is interested only in the <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bound_state" title=3D"Bound state">bound stat=
e</a> solutions of the Schr=C3=B6dinger equation, one looks for <span class=
=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">=CF=88<sub>E</sub></span> wi=
thin the space of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Square-integrabl=
e_function" title=3D"Square-integrable function">square integrable</a> func=
tions. Since this space is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hilbe=
rt_space" title=3D"Hilbert space">Hilbert space</a> with a well-defined <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scalar_product" class=3D"mw-redirect"=
 title=3D"Scalar product">scalar product</a>, one can introduce a <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Basis_(linear_algebra)" title=3D"Basis (l=
inear algebra)">basis set</a> in which <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=
=3D"font-style:italic;">=CF=88<sub>E</sub></span> and <span class=3D"texhtm=
l mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">H</span> can be represented as a one-d=
imensional array (i.e., a vector) and a matrix respectively. This allows on=
e to represent the Schr=C3=B6dinger equation in a matrix form.
</p><p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bra%E2%80%93ket_notatio=
n" title=3D"Bra=E2=80=93ket notation">bra=E2=80=93ket notation</a> is often=
 used in this context. A vector, which represents a state of the system, in=
 the Hilbert space of square integrable functions is represented by <span c=
lass=3D"texhtml"><span class=3D"nowrap">|=CE=A8<sub><i>E</i></sub>=E2=9F=A9=
</span></span>. In this notation, the Schr=C3=B6dinger equation is:
<span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-block"><span class=3D"mwe-=
math-mathml-display mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math di=
splay=3D"block" xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\d=
isplaystyle H|\Psi _{E}\rangle =3DE|\Psi _{E}\rangle }">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
