        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mo stretchy=3D"false">|</mo>
        </mrow>
        <msub>
          <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">=CE=A8<!-- =CE=A8 --></mi>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mi>E</mi>
          </mrow>
        </msub>
        <mo fence=3D"false" stretchy=3D"false">=E2=9F=A9<!-- =E2=9F=A9 --><=
/mo>
        <mo>=3D</mo>
        <mi>E</mi>
        <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
          <mo stretchy=3D"false">|</mo>
        </mrow>
        <msub>
          <mi mathvariant=3D"normal">=CE=A8<!-- =CE=A8 --></mi>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mi>E</mi>
          </mrow>
        </msub>
        <mo fence=3D"false" stretchy=3D"false">=E2=9F=A9<!-- =E2=9F=A9 --><=
/mo>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle H|\Psi _{E}\r=
angle =3DE|\Psi _{E}\rangle }</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/629f94a4338f4b85c597313e6f194135f7b6c751" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-display mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertica=
l-align: -0.838ex; width:16.633ex; height:2.843ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle H=
|\Psi _{E}\rangle =3DE|\Psi _{E}\rangle }"></span>
where <span class=3D"texhtml"><span class=3D"nowrap">|=CE=A8<sub><i>E</i></=
sub>=E2=9F=A9</span></span> is an <b><dfn>eigenstate</dfn></b> of <span cla=
ss=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">H</span>, and <span class=
=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">E</span> represents the eige=
nvalue. <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">H</span> =
is an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Observable" title=3D"Observa=
ble">observable</a> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Self-adjoint_o=
perator" title=3D"Self-adjoint operator">self-adjoint operator</a>, the inf=
inite-dimensional analog of Hermitian matrices. As in the matrix case, in t=
he equation above <span class=3D"texhtml"><span style=3D"padding-right:0.15=
em;"><i>H</i></span><span class=3D"nowrap">|=CE=A8<sub><i>E</i></sub>=E2=9F=
=A9</span></span> is understood to be the vector obtained by application of=
 the transformation <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic=
;">H</span> to <span class=3D"texhtml"><span class=3D"nowrap">|=CE=A8<sub><=
i>E</i></sub>=E2=9F=A9</span></span>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Wave_transport">Wave transp=
ort</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracke=
t">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DEigenval=
ues_and_eigenvectors&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D43" title=3D"Edit sect=
ion: Wave transport"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bra=
cket">]</span></span></div>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Light" title=3D"Light">Light</a=
>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Acoustic_wave" title=3D"Acousti=
c wave">acoustic waves</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mi=
crowave" title=3D"Microwave">microwaves</a> are randomly <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Scattering_theory" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Sc=
attering theory">scattered</a> numerous times when traversing a static <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DDisordered_system&amp;a=
ction=3Dedit&amp;redlink=3D1" class=3D"new" title=3D"Disordered system (pag=
e does not exist)">disordered system</a>. Even though multiple scattering r=
epeatedly randomizes the waves, ultimately coherent wave transport through =
the system is a deterministic process which can be described by a field tra=
nsmission matrix <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>t</b></span>.<sup id=3D"cite_re=
f-FOOTNOTEVellekoopMosk20072309=E2=80=932311_49-0" class=3D"reference"><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eigenvalues_and_eigenvectors#cite_note=
-FOOTNOTEVellekoopMosk20072309%E2%80%932311-49"><span class=3D"cite-bracket=
">[</span>44<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_=
ref-FOOTNOTERotterGigan201715005_50-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eigenvalues_and_eigenvectors#cite_note-FOOTNOTERot=
terGigan201715005-50"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>45<span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The eigenvectors of the transmission oper=
ator <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>t</b><sup>=E2=80=A0</sup><b>t</b></span> fo=
rm a set of disorder-specific input wavefronts which enable waves to couple=
 into the disordered system's eigenchannels: the independent pathways waves=
 can travel through the system. The eigenvalues, <span class=3D"texhtml mva=
r" style=3D"font-style:italic;">=CF=84</span>, of <span class=3D"texhtml"><=
b>t</b><sup>=E2=80=A0</sup><b>t</b></span> correspond to the intensity tran=
smittance associated with each eigenchannel. One of the remarkable properti=
es of the transmission operator of diffusive systems is their bimodal eigen=
value distribution with <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>=CF=84</i><sub>max</sub>=
 =3D 1</span> and <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>=CF=84</i><sub>min</sub> =3D 0=
</span>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTERotterGigan201715005_50-1" class=3D"ref=
erence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eigenvalues_and_eigenvecto=
rs#cite_note-FOOTNOTERotterGigan201715005-50"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
[</span>45<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Furthermore, one =
of the striking properties of open eigenchannels, beyond the perfect transm=
ittance, is the statistically robust spatial profile of the eigenchannels.<=
sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEBenderYamilovYilmazCao2020_51-0" class=3D"refere=
nce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eigenvalues_and_eigenvectors#=
cite_note-FOOTNOTEBenderYamilovYilmazCao2020-51"><span class=3D"cite-bracke=
t">[</span>46<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Molecular_orbitals">Molecul=
ar orbitals</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsectio=
n-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3D=
Eigenvalues_and_eigenvectors&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D44" title=3D"E=
dit section: Molecular orbitals"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-edi=
tsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quantum_mechanics" title=3D"=
Quantum mechanics">quantum mechanics</a>, and in particular in <a href=3D"h=
ttps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Atomic_physics" title=3D"Atomic physics">atomi=
c</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Molecular_physics" title=
=3D"Molecular physics">molecular physics</a>, within the <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hartree%E2%80%93Fock" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D=
"Hartree=E2=80=93Fock">Hartree=E2=80=93Fock</a> theory, the <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Atomic_orbital" title=3D"Atomic orbital">atomic</=
a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Molecular_orbital" title=3D=
"Molecular orbital">molecular orbitals</a> can be defined by the eigenvecto=
rs of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fock_operator" class=3D"=
mw-redirect" title=3D"Fock operator">Fock operator</a>. The corresponding e=
igenvalues are interpreted as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ioni=
zation_potential" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Ionization potential">ioni=
zation potentials</a> via <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Koopmans=
%27_theorem" title=3D"Koopmans' theorem">Koopmans' theorem</a>. In this cas=
e, the term eigenvector is used in a somewhat more general meaning, since t=
he Fock operator is explicitly dependent on the orbitals and their eigenval=
ues. Thus, if one wants to underline this aspect, one speaks of nonlinear e=
igenvalue problems. Such equations are usually solved by an <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Iteration" title=3D"Iteration">iteration</a> proc=
edure, called in this case <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Self-co=
nsistent_field" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Self-consistent field">self-=
consistent field</a> method. In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Qu=
antum_chemistry" title=3D"Quantum chemistry">quantum chemistry</a>, one oft=
en represents the Hartree=E2=80=93Fock equation in a non-<a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orthogonal" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Orthogona=
l">orthogonal</a> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Basis_set_(chemi=
stry)" title=3D"Basis set (chemistry)">basis set</a>. This particular repre=
sentation is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Generalized_eigenva=
lue_problem" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Generalized eigenvalue problem"=
>generalized eigenvalue problem</a> called <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Roothaan_equations" title=3D"Roothaan equations">Roothaan equation=
s</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Geology_and_glaciology">Geo=
logy and glaciology</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-ed=
itsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?=
title=3DEigenvalues_and_eigenvectors&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D45" ti=
tle=3D"Edit section: Geology and glaciology"><span>edit</span></a><span cla=
ss=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<table class=3D"box-Technical plainlinks metadata ambox ambox-style ambox-t=
echnical" role=3D"presentation"><tbody><tr><td class=3D"mbox-image"><div cl=
ass=3D"mbox-image-div"><span typeof=3D"mw:File"><span><img alt=3D"" src=3D"=
https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/f/f2/Edit-clear.svg/40px-Ed=
it-clear.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"40" height=3D"40" class=3D"mw=
-file-element" data-file-width=3D"48" data-file-height=3D"48"></span></span=
></div></td><td class=3D"mbox-text"><div class=3D"mbox-text-span">This sect=
ion <b>may be too technical for most readers to understand</b>.<span class=
=3D"hide-when-compact"> Please <a class=3D"external text" href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DEigenvalues_and_eigenvectors&amp;action=
=3Dedit">help improve it</a> to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wi=
kipedia:Make_technical_articles_understandable" title=3D"Wikipedia:Make tec=
hnical articles understandable">make it understandable to non-experts</a>, =
without removing the technical details.</span>  <span class=3D"date-contain=
er"><i>(<span class=3D"date">December 2023</span>)</i></span><span class=3D=
"hide-when-compact"><i> (<small><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/He=
lp:Maintenance_template_removal" title=3D"Help:Maintenance template removal=
">Learn how and when to remove this message</a></small>)</i></span></div></=
td></tr></tbody></table>
<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geology" title=3D"Geology">g=
eology</a>, especially in the study of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Glacial_till" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Glacial till">glacial til=
l</a>, eigenvectors and eigenvalues are used as a method by which a mass of=
 information of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Clastic_rock" ti=
tle=3D"Clastic rock">clast's</a> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/F=
abric_(geology)" title=3D"Fabric (geology)">fabric</a> can be summarized in=
 a 3-D space by six numbers. In the field, a geologist may collect such dat=
a for hundreds or thousands of clasts in a soil sample, which can be compar=
ed graphically or as a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stereograph=
ic_projection" title=3D"Stereographic projection">stereographic projection<=
/a>. Graphically, many geologists use a Tri-Plot (Sneed and Folk) diagram,.=
<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEGrahamMidgley20001473=E2=80=931477_52-0" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eigenvalues_and_eig=
envectors#cite_note-FOOTNOTEGrahamMidgley20001473%E2%80%931477-52"><span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>47<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></s=
up><sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTESneedFolk1958114=E2=80=93150_53-0" class=3D"=
reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eigenvalues_and_eigenve=
ctors#cite_note-FOOTNOTESneedFolk1958114%E2%80%93150-53"><span class=3D"cit=
e-bracket">[</span>48<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> A ster=
eographic projection projects 3-dimensional spaces onto a two-dimensional p=
lane. A type of stereographic projection is Wulff Net, which is commonly us=
ed in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Crystallography" title=3D"Cr=
ystallography">crystallography</a> to create <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Stereograms" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Stereograms">stereog=
rams</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEKnox-RobinsonGardoll1998243_54-0" clas=
s=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eigenvalues_and_ei=
genvectors#cite_note-FOOTNOTEKnox-RobinsonGardoll1998243-54"><span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">[</span>49<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The output for the orientation tensor is in the three orthogonal (pe=
rpendicular) axes of space. The three eigenvectors are ordered <span class=
=3D"texhtml"><b>v</b><sub>1</sub></span>, <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>v</b><=
sub>2</sub></span>, <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>v</b><sub>3</sub></span> by =
their eigenvalues <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>E</i><sub>1</sub> =E2=89=A5</s=
pan> <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>E</i><sub>2</sub> =E2=89=A5 <i>E</i><sub>3<=
/sub></span>;<sup id=3D"cite_ref-55" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eigenvalues_and_eigenvectors#cite_note-55"><span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>50<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></su=
p>
<span class=3D"texhtml"><b>v</b><sub>1</sub></span> then is the primary ori=
entation/dip of clast, <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>v</b><sub>2</sub></span> =
is the secondary and <span class=3D"texhtml"><b>v</b><sub>3</sub></span> is=
 the tertiary, in terms of strength. The clast orientation is defined as th=
e direction of the eigenvector, on a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Compass_rose" title=3D"Compass rose">compass rose</a> of <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Turn_(geometry)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"T=
urn (geometry)">360=C2=B0</a>. Dip is measured as the eigenvalue, the modul=
us of the tensor: this is valued from 0=C2=B0 (no dip) to 90=C2=B0 (vertica=
l). The relative values of <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>E</i><sub>1</sub></sp=
an>, <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>E</i><sub>2</sub></span>, and <span class=
=3D"texhtml"><i>E</i><sub>3</sub></span> are dictated by the nature of the =
sediment's fabric. If <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>E</i><sub>1</sub> =3D</spa=
n> <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>E</i><sub>2</sub> =3D <i>E</i><sub>3</sub></s=
pan>, the fabric is said to be isotropic. If <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>E</=
i><sub>1</sub> =3D</span> <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>E</i><sub>2</sub> &gt;=
 <i>E</i><sub>3</sub></span>, the fabric is said to be planar. If <span cla=
ss=3D"texhtml"><i>E</i><sub>1</sub> &gt;</span> <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>=
E</i><sub>2</sub> &gt; <i>E</i><sub>3</sub></span>, the fabric is said to b=
e linear.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEBennEvans2004103=E2=80=93107_56-0" cla=
ss=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eigenvalues_and_e=
igenvectors#cite_note-FOOTNOTEBennEvans2004103%E2%80%93107-56"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>51<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Basic_reproduction_number">=
Basic reproduction number</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D=
"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/inde=
x.php?title=3DEigenvalues_and_eigenvectors&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D=
46" title=3D"Edit section: Basic reproduction number"><span>edit</span></a>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Basic_reproduction_n=
umber" title=3D"Basic reproduction number">Basic reproduction number</a></d=
iv>
<p>The basic reproduction number (<span class=3D"texhtml"><i>R</i><sub>0</s=
ub></span>) is a fundamental number in the study of how infectious diseases=
 spread. If one infectious person is put into a population of completely su=
sceptible people, then <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>R</i><sub>0</sub></span> =
is the average number of people that one typical infectious person will inf=
ect. The generation time of an infection is the time, <span class=3D"texhtm=
l mvar" style=3D"font-style:italic;">t<sub>G</sub></span>, from one person =
becoming infected to the next person becoming infected. In a heterogeneous =
population, the next generation matrix defines how many people in the popul=
ation will become infected after time <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D=
"font-style:italic;">t<sub>G</sub></span> has passed. The value <span class=
=3D"texhtml"><i>R</i><sub>0</sub></span> is then the largest eigenvalue of =
the next generation matrix.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEDiekmannHeesterbeekM=
etz1990365=E2=80=93382_57-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Eigenvalues_and_eigenvectors#cite_note-FOOTNOTEDiekmannHeest=
erbeekMetz1990365%E2%80%93382-57"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>52<s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEHe=
esterbeekDiekmann2000_58-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Eigenvalues_and_eigenvectors#cite_note-FOOTNOTEHeesterbeekDie=
kmann2000-58"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>53<span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Eigenfaces">Eigenfaces</h3>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</sp=
an><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DEigenvalues_and_=
eigenvectors&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D47" title=3D"Edit section: Eig=
enfaces"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</spa=
n></span></div>
<figure typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/F=
ile:Eigenfaces.png" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://uploa=
d.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/67/Eigenfaces.png/250px-Eigenface=
s.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"200" height=3D"239" class=3D"mw-file-ele=
ment" data-file-width=3D"357" data-file-height=3D"426"></a><figcaption><a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eigenface" title=3D"Eigenface">Eigenfa=
ces</a> as examples of eigenvectors</figcaption></figure>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eigenface" title=3D"=
Eigenface">Eigenface</a></div>
<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Image_processing" class=3D"m=
w-redirect" title=3D"Image processing">image processing</a>, processed imag=
es of faces can be seen as vectors whose components are the <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brightness" title=3D"Brightness">brightnesses</a>=
 of each <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pixel" title=3D"Pixel">pi=
xel</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-FOOTNOTEXirouhakisVotsisDelopoulus1999_59-0" cl=
ass=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eigenvalues_and_=
eigenvectors#cite_note-FOOTNOTEXirouhakisVotsisDelopoulus1999-59"><span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>54<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></su=
p> The dimension of this vector space is the number of pixels. The eigenvec=
tors of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Covariance_matrix" tit=
le=3D"Covariance matrix">covariance matrix</a> associated with a large set =
of normalized pictures of faces are called <b><a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Eigenface" title=3D"Eigenface">eigenfaces</a></b>; this is an e=
xample of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Principal_component_anal=
ysis" title=3D"Principal component analysis">principal component analysis</=
a>. They are very useful for expressing any face image as a <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_combination" title=3D"Linear combination">=
linear combination</a> of some of them. In the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Facial_recognition_system" title=3D"Facial recognition system"=
>facial recognition</a> branch of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Biometrics" title=3D"Biometrics">biometrics</a>, eigenfaces provide a means=
 of applying <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Data_compression" tit=
le=3D"Data compression">data compression</a> to faces for <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Recognition_of_human_individuals" class=3D"mw-redir=
ect" title=3D"Recognition of human individuals">identification</a> purposes=
. Research related to eigen vision systems determining hand gestures has al=
so been made.
</p><p>Similar to this concept, <b>eigenvoices</b> represent the general di=
rection of variability in human pronunciations of a particular utterance, s=
uch as a word in a language. Based on a linear combination of such eigenvoi=
ces, a new voice pronunciation of the word can be constructed. These concep=
ts have been found useful in automatic speech recognition systems for speak=
er adaptation.
</p>
